article.description: Tan White hit five 3-pointers as Mississippi State manhandled Manhattan.
article.headline: Bulldogs hold Lady Jaspers to 14 points in first half
article.linkText: Defense helps Mississippi St. dominate Manhattan
article.story:
ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- It took Tan White and LaToya Thomas
just 54 seconds Saturday to get Mississippi State comfortable and
confident in the NCAA Tournament.

	   Thomas, the All American forward, hit a 15-foot jumper, and
White, the Lady Bulldogs' quick point guard, scored on a bank shot
in the opening minute. From there, the No. 3 seeded Lady Bulldogs
cruised into the second round of the Midwest Regional with a 73-47
win over Manhattan.

	   White and Thomas each finished with 22 points and Thomas also
had 13 rebounds.

	   "You expect key players to step up and be leaders of their
team," said Mississippi State coach Sharon Fanning. "They did
what's expected of them. Tan has a lot of confidence in her
shooting, and this year what I've seen in her is her ability to
focus and be ready to play."

	   Mississippi State (24-7) didn't need much help but got plenty,
anyway, from Manhattan (20-10). The Lady Jaspers, 0-4 in NCAA
Tournament games, missed their first 13 shots and 21 of their first
24.

 Mississippi State advances to play New Mexico in the second
round.


	   Guard Siobhan Kilkenny got the Lady Jaspers on the board with an
offensive rebound basket with 12:14 left in the first half to halt
an 11-0 run by Mississippi State.

	  "We struggled very, very early," Manhattan coach Sal Buscaglia
said. "It took us a good deal of time, probably eight minutes to
score. I think the jitters were a really big part of that."

	   Kilkenny said the Lady Jaspers' inability to hit shots early was
the biggest difference.

	 "I'm not so sure if it was nerves or what it was, but the ball
just wasn't falling for us," she said.

	   It didn't get much better for Manhattan. By halftime the score
was 36-14 -- a season-low first half for the Lady Jaspers. They
finished the game hitting just 17 of 69 shots (24 percent).

	   Thomas, a forward, and White, the point guard, were too tough a
combination for Manhattan, which came in having won 17 of its last
18 games.

	   "I'm a lot more confident this year," said White, who finished
her freshman season by hitting just three of 14 shots in
Mississippi State's 77-55 loss to Texas Tech in the second round of
last year's NCAA Tournament. "Coming into this game, I was more
focused."

	   The 6-foot-2 Thomas, who led the SEC in scoring four straight
seasons and came into the tournament averaging 25.6 points a game,
dominated the middle. She hit nine of 14 shots and led Mississippi
State to a 51-36 edge in rebounding.

	   White riddled Manhattan's defense with her outside shooting. Her
two 3-pointers early in the second half and a layup by Thomas with
16:00 left gave Mississippi State a 46-19 lead.

	   Rosalee Mason scored 16 points for Manhattan and Kilkenny had
13.

	   With New Mexico playing Miami in the second game, the Lobo fans
had nearly filled The Pit by midway through the second half of the
Mississippi State-Manhattan game. They got behind the underdog Lady
Jaspers, cheering loudly each time they scored, but by then the
Lady Bulldogs' lead was out of reach.

	   Mississippi State advances to play the winner of the game
between New Mexico and Miami in Monday's second round.
